{"title_page": "Phil Williams (Welsh politician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox AM\n|honorific-prefix = Professor \n|name         = Phil Williams\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image        = \n|constituency_AM = [[South Wales East (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|South Wales East]] \n|assembly     = National Assembly for Wales{{!}}Welsh\n|majority     = \n|term_start   = 6 May 1999\n|term_end     = 1 May 2003\n|predecessor  = [[Government of Wales Act 1998|''New Assembly'']]\n|successor    = [[Laura Anne Jones]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1939|01|11|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Tredegar]]\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|2003|06|10|1939|01|11|df=yes}}\n|death_place  = [[Cardiff]]\n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = Philip James Stradling Williams\n|nationality  = \n|party        = [[Plaid Cymru]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = \n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = [[Clare College, Cambridge]]\n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|website      = \n}}\nProfessor '''Philip James Stradling Williams''' (11 January 1939 \u2013 10 June 2003) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[politician]] for  [[Plaid Cymru]] and [[scientist]].\n\n==Background==\nWilliams was born in [[Tredegar]] in the industrial valleys of south Wales and grew up in [[Bargoed]], another industrial town. He was educated at [[Lewis School, Pengam]] and [[Clare College, Cambridge]],<ref name=\"obit\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-phil-williams-548282.html Professor Phil Williams obituary], ''The Independent'' 10 November 2003 : Retrieved 10 November 2010</ref> and became a leading [[space scientist]]. He was appointed Professor of [[Solar Terrestrial Physics]] at the [[University of Wales, Aberystwyth|University College of Wales, Aberystwyth]], and simultaneously became economic spokesman for [[Plaid Cymru]].\n\n==Political career==\nHe contested the [[1968 Caerphilly by-election]], where he came close to unseating Labour in a safe seat, and became the second Chairman of Plaid Cymru in 1970, a post he held until 1976; when he became Vice President of the party. He was responsible for policy and research in the party for many years.\n\nFrom 1999 to 2003, he was a [[Member of the National Assembly for Wales|Member]] of the [[National Assembly for Wales]] for the electoral region of [[South Wales East]]. Williams also stood for election in [[Blaenau Gwent (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Blaenau Gwent]] in 1999 and got 21% of the vote.\n\n==Return to science and death==\nHe stood down as an [[Member of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] in 2003 to work on a research project to study the inner workings of the [[sun]] from the [[observatory]] near the [[North Pole]]. In 2001, he was voted [[Welsh Politician of the Year]], and he was being pressured by former colleagues to become the next president of his party, following the resignation of [[Ieuan Wyn Jones]] as president. Shortly after standing down from the [[Welsh Assembly]] he suffered a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] while visiting the \"A Touch of Class\" (now known as Twice as Nice) massage parlour  in Cardiff<ref>[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/wales/story/0,9061,975806,00.html Welsh politician died in massage parlour], The Guardian, 2003, accessed 10 November 2010</ref> and was pronounced dead shortly afterwards.\nHi I like u\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* Rishbeth, Henry. [https://web.archive.org/web/20040815232908/http://www.blackwellpublishing.com/products/journals/aag/AAG_October03/aag_44538.htm \"Obituary: P J S Williams 1939\u20132003\"], ''[[Astronomy & Geophysics]]'', 44(5), 2003.\n*[http://www.plaidcymru.org/ Plaid Cymru \u2013 the Party of Wales Website]\n\n==Offices held==\n{{start box}}\n{{s-par|wal}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] for [[South Wales East (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|South Wales East]] \n  | years  = [[1999 National Assembly for Wales election|1999]] \u2013 [[2003 National Assembly for Wales election|2003]]\n  | before=(new post)\n  | after=[[Laura Anne Jones]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title = Chair of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years = 1970\u20131976 | before = [[Chris Rees]] | after = [[Eurfyl ap Gwilym]]}}\n{{succession box| title=Vice President of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years=1968\u20131970 | before=[[Edward Millward]] | after=[[Robyn Lewis]]}}\n{{succession box| title=Vice President of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years=1976\u20131978 | before=[[Robyn Lewis]] | after=[[Dafydd Ellis Thomas]]}}\n{{succession box| title=Vice President of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years=1982\u20131984 | before=[[Dafydd Ellis Thomas]] | after=[[Dafydd Iwan]]}}\n{{end box}}\n{{Plaid Cymru}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Phil}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Tredegar]]\n[[Category:Academics of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru Members of the National Assembly for Wales]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 1999\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru politicians]]\n[[Category:Welsh space scientists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Lewis School, Pengam]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Welsh-speaking politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox AM\n|honorific-prefix = Professor \n|name         = Phil Williams\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image        = \n|constituency_AM = [[South Wales East (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|South Wales East]] \n|assembly     = National Assembly for Wales{{!}}Welsh\n|majority     = \n|term_start   = 6 May 1999\n|term_end     = 1 May 2003\n|predecessor  = [[Government of Wales Act 1998|''New Assembly'']]\n|successor    = [[Laura Anne Jones]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1939|01|11|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Tredegar]]\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|2003|06|10|1939|01|11|df=yes}}\n|death_place  = [[Cardiff]]\n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = Philip James Stradling Williams\n|nationality  = \n|party        = [[Plaid Cymru]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = \n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = [[Clare College, Cambridge]]\n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|website      = \n}}\nProfessor '''Philip James Stradling Williams''' (11 January 1939 \u2013 10 June 2003) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[politician]] for  [[Plaid Cymru]] and [[scientist]].\n\n==Background==\nWilliams was born in [[Tredegar]] in the industrial valleys of south Wales and grew up in [[Bargoed]], another industrial town. He was educated at [[Lewis School, Pengam]] and [[Clare College, Cambridge]],<ref name=\"obit\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-phil-williams-548282.html Professor Phil Williams obituary], ''The Independent'' 10 November 2003 : Retrieved 10 November 2010</ref> and became a leading [[space scientist]]. He was appointed Professor of [[Solar Terrestrial Physics]] at the [[University of Wales, Aberystwyth|University College of Wales, Aberystwyth]], and simultaneously became economic spokesman for [[Plaid Cymru]].\n\n==Political career==\nHe contested the [[1968 Caerphilly by-election]], where he came close to unseating Labour in a safe seat, and became the second Chairman of Plaid Cymru in 1970, a post he held until 1976; when he became Vice President of the party. He was responsible for policy and research in the party for many years.\n\nFrom 1999 to 2003, he was a [[Member of the National Assembly for Wales|Member]] of the [[National Assembly for Wales]] for the electoral region of [[South Wales East]]. Williams also stood for election in [[Blaenau Gwent (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Blaenau Gwent]] in 1999 and got 21% of the vote.\n\n==Return to science and death==\nHe stood down as an [[Member of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] in 2003 to work on a research project to study the inner workings of the [[sun]] from the [[observatory]] near the [[North Pole]]. In 2001, he was voted [[Welsh Politician of the Year]], and he was being pressured by former colleagues to become the next president of his party, following the resignation of [[Ieuan Wyn Jones]] as president. Shortly after standing down from the [[Welsh Assembly]] he suffered a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] while visiting the \"A Touch of Class\" (now known as Twice as Nice) massage parlour  in Cardiff<ref>[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/wales/story/0,9061,975806,00.html Welsh politician died in massage parlour], The Guardian, 2003, accessed 10 November 2010</ref> and was pronounced dead shortly afterwards.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* Rishbeth, Henry. [https://web.archive.org/web/20040815232908/http://www.blackwellpublishing.com/products/journals/aag/AAG_October03/aag_44538.htm \"Obituary: P J S Williams 1939\u20132003\"], ''[[Astronomy & Geophysics]]'', 44(5), 2003.\n*[http://www.plaidcymru.org/ Plaid Cymru \u2013 the Party of Wales Website]\n\n==Offices held==\n{{start box}}\n{{s-par|wal}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] for [[South Wales East (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|South Wales East]] \n  | years  = [[1999 National Assembly for Wales election|1999]] \u2013 [[2003 National Assembly for Wales election|2003]]\n  | before=(new post)\n  | after=[[Laura Anne Jones]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title = Chair of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years = 1970\u20131976 | before = [[Chris Rees]] | after = [[Eurfyl ap Gwilym]]}}\n{{succession box| title=Vice President of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years=1968\u20131970 | before=[[Edward Millward]] | after=[[Robyn Lewis]]}}\n{{succession box| title=Vice President of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years=1976\u20131978 | before=[[Robyn Lewis]] | after=[[Dafydd Ellis Thomas]]}}\n{{succession box| title=Vice President of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years=1982\u20131984 | before=[[Dafydd Ellis Thomas]] | after=[[Dafydd Iwan]]}}\n{{end box}}\n{{Plaid Cymru}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Phil}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Tredegar]]\n[[Category:Academics of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru Members of the National Assembly for Wales]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 1999\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru politicians]]\n[[Category:Welsh space scientists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Lewis School, Pengam]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Welsh-speaking politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh scientists]]\n", "name_user": "2.123.192.193", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReturn to science and death)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil_Williams_(Welsh_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Kartir", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Kartir\n| image                     = Naqshe Rajab Darafsh Ordibehesht 93 (1).jpg\n| image_size                = 260px\n| caption                   = [[Kartir's inscription at Naqsh-e Rajab]]\n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = 3rd century\n| birth_place               = [[Sasanian Empire|Iran]]\n| death_date                = 3rd century\n| death_place               = Iran\n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| influences                = \n| influenced                = \n| spouse                    =\n| children                  =\n| father                    =\n}}\n'''Kartir''' (also spelled '''Karder''', '''Karter''' and '''Kerdir'''; [[Middle Persian]]: \ud802\udf6a\ud802\udf6b\ud802\udf72\ud802\udf69\ud802\udf6b ''Kard\u012br'') was a powerful and influential [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] priest during the reigns of four Sasanian kings in the 3rd-century. His name is cited in the inscriptions of [[Shapur I]] (as well as in the ''[[Shapur I's inscription at the Ka'ba-ye Zartosht|Res Gestae Divi Saporis]]'') and the [[Paikuli inscription]] of [[Narseh]]. Kartir also had inscriptions of his own made in the present-day [[Fars Province]] (then known as [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Pars]]). His inscriptions narrates his rise to power throughout the reigns of Shapur I ({{reign|240|270}}), [[Hormizd I]] ({{reign|270|271}}), [[Bahram I]] ({{reign|271|274}}), and [[Bahram II]] ({{reign|274|293}}). During the brief reign of Bahram II's son and successor [[Bahram III]], Kartir was amongst the nobles who supported the rebellion of Narseh, who overthrew Bahram III and ascended the throne. During Narseh's reign, Kartir fades into obscurity, due not doing anything noteworthy as high priest.\n\n== Name ==\nKartir's name is spelled in several ways in the engravings; Middle Persian <kltyl, kltyly, krtyr, kltyr>, [[Parthian language|Parthian]] <krtyr>, [[Greek language|Greek]] ''Karteir'', and [[Coptic language|Coptic]] ''Kardel''. The name was also used in the northeastern Iranian world, being spelt <krt'yr> in [[Sogdian language|Sogdian]] and as ''Kirdira'' in [[Bactrian language|Bactrian]].{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}}\n\n== Biography ==\n===Under Shapur I and Hormizd I===\n[[Image:Gold coin of Shapur I, Ctesiphon mint.jpg|thumb|Coin of [[Shapur I]].]]\nKartir may have been a [[eunuch]], due to being depicted without a beard in the Sasanian reliefs.{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} He first appears in historical records in [[Shapur I's inscription at the Ka'ba-ye Zartosht]], which was most likely created between 260\u2013262. Kartir is the only religious bureaucrat mentioned in the inscription.{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} Shapur I, a \"lukewarm Zoroastrian\",{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} was known for his tolerance towards other religions. Although admiring the teachings of his own religion and encouraging the [[Zoroastrian]] clergy, Shapur I let the [[Judaism|Jews]], [[Christianity|Christians]], [[Buddhism|Buddhists]], and [[Hinduism|Hindus]] to freely practice their religion.{{sfn|Kia|2016|p=234}} He was also friendly towards the founder of [[Manichaeism]], [[Mani (prophet)|Mani]], whom he allowed to preach freely and even to be an escort in his military expeditions.{{sfn|Kia|2016|p=234}} \n[[Image:Rare coin of Hormizd I.jpg|left|thumb|Coin of [[Hormizd I]].]]\nShapur I religious practices seems to have been somewhat unusual, with animal sacrifice being made for the soul of the kings and queens of the Sasanian family.{{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=9}}{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} This presumably seemed \"pagan\" to Zoroastrian priests. {{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=9}} Kartir, who \"abhorred animal sacrifice\" was unable to stop Shapur I from doing them.{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} Shapur I died in 270, and was succeeded by [[Hormizd I]], who gave Kartir clothes that were worn by the upper class, the cap and belt (''kul\u0101f ud kamarband'') and appointed him as the chief priest (''[[mobad|mowbed]]'').{{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=76}}\n\nHormizd I died the following year; Bahram I, who was never considered a candidate for succession of the throne by his father, ascended the throne with the aid of Kartir, whose authority and influence had greatly increased.{{sfn|Shahbazi|1988|pp=514\u2013522}} Bahram I then made a settlement with his brother [[Narseh]] to give up his entitlement to the throne in return for the governorship of the important frontier province of [[Sasanian Armenia|Armenia]], which was constantly the subject of war between the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] and Sasanian Empires.{{sfn|Weber|2016}} Narseh held the title of ''Vazurg \u0160\u0101h Armin\u0101n'' (\"Great King of Armenia\"), which was used by the heir to the throne.{{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=11}} Nevertheless, Narseh still most likely viewed Bahram I as a usurper.{{sfn|Shahbazi|1988|pp=514\u2013522}}\n\n===Under Bahram I===\n[[Image:Coin of the Sasanian king Bahram I, Ctesiphon mint.jpg|thumb|Coin of [[Bahram I]].]]\nThe previous Sasanian shahs had pursued a policy of religious tolerance towards the non-Zoroastrian minorities in the empire. However, with Bahram I's accession to the throne, and the rise of the authority of the Zoroastrian priesthood and the increasing influence of Kartir, this changed; when Mani reached the city of [[Gundishapur]], much uproar occurred, in the same fashion as [[Jesus]]' entry into [[Jerusalem]].{{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=74}} Kartir, along with other Zoroastrian priests protested and made Bahram I have Mani imprisoned and sentenced to death in 274.{{sfn|Daniel|2012|p=61}}{{sfn|Shahbazi|1988|pp=514\u2013522}}\n\nMani's death was followed by the persecution of his followers by Kartir and the Zoroastrian clergy, who used the persecution of religious minorities as a method to increase and spread their vast influence.{{sfn|Kia|2016|p=234}} Mani was seen by the Zoroastrian clergy as heterogeneous philosopher and a threatening pagan who was presenting an obscure perception of Zoroastrianism, which had been tainted by non-Zoroastrian (i.e., Jewish, Buddhist, and Christian) ideas.{{sfn|Kia|2016|p=234}} With the backing of Bahram I, Kartir laid foundations to a Zoroastrian state church.{{sfn|Shahbazi|1988|pp=514\u2013522}}{{sfn|Kia|2016|p=234}} As a result, Bahram I became applauded in Sasanian-based sources as a \"benevolent and worthy king.\"{{sfn|Shahbazi|1988|pp=514\u2013522}} His son [[Bahram II]] succeeded him as shah; he may have been aided by Kartir to ascend the throne instead of Narseh.{{sfn|Daryaee|Rezakhani|2017|p=157}}{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} This most likely frustrated Narseh, who had now been neglected from succession several times.{{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=11}}\n\n=== Under Bahram II, Bahram III and Narseh ===\n[[Image:Silver coin of Bahram II.jpg|thumb|Coin of [[Bahram II]].]]\n[[Image:NarsehCoinHistoryofIran.jpg|thumb|right|Coin of [[Narseh]].]]\nBahram II, like his father, received Kartir well. He saw him as his mentor, and handed out several honors to Kartir, giving him the rank of grandee (''[[wuzurgan]]''), and appointing him as the supreme judge (''dadwar'') of the whole empire, which indicates that thenceforth priests were given the office of judge.{{sfn|Shahbazi|1988|pp=514-522}}{{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=76}} Kartir was also appointed the steward of the [[Anahid fire-temple]] at [[Istakhr]], which had originally been under the care of the Sasanian family.{{sfn|Shahbazi|1988|pp=514-522}}{{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=11}} The Sasanian kings thus lost much of their religious authority in the empire. The clergy from now on served as judges all over the country, with court cases most likely being based on Zoroastrian jurisprudence, with the exception of when representatives of other religions had conflicts with each other.{{sfn|Daryaee|2014|p=11}}\n\nIt is thus under Bahram II that Kartir unquestionably becomes a powerful figure in the empire; the latter claimed on his inscription that he \"struck down\" the non-Zoroastrian minorities, such as the [[Christianity|Christians]], [[Jews]], [[Mandaeans]], [[Manichaeism|Manichaeans]], and [[Buddhism|Buddhists]].{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} According to the modern historian Parvaneh Pourshariati: \"it is not clear, however, to what extent Kartir's declarations reflect the actual implementation, or for that matter, success, of the measures he is supposed to have promoted.\"{{sfn|Pourshariati|2018|p=348}} Indeed, Jewish and Christian sources, for example, makes no mention of persecutions during this period.{{sfn|Pourshariati|2018|p=348}}{{sfn|Payne|2015|p=24}} Before Bahram II, all the previous Sasanian shahs had been \"lukewarm Zoroastrians.\"{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} He died in 293 and was succeeded by his son [[Bahram III]].\n\nFour months into Bahram III's reign, Narseh was summoned to [[Mesopotamia]] at the request of many members of the Iranian nobility. He met them in the passage of Paikuli in the province of [[Beth Garmai|Garamig]], where he was firmly approved and likely also declared shah for the first time.{{sfn|Weber|2016}} The reasons behind the nobles favour of Narseh might have been due to his jurisdiction as governor, his image as an advocate of the [[Zoroastrian]] religion and as an insurer for harmony and prosperity of the empire.{{sfn|Weber|2016}} His ancestry from the early Sasanian family probably also played a role.{{sfn|Weber|2016}} Kartir was one of those nobles who supported Narseh, which is attested in the [[Paikuli inscription]].{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} Narseh's reign marked the return to the policy of religious tolerance which had been practiced by his father.{{sfn|Weber|2016}} Kartir fades into obscurity in historical records under Narseh, due to not doing anything noteworthy as high priest.{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}}\n\n== Legacy and assessment ==\nAccording to the modern historian Prods Oktor Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8, \"In both Iranist and non-Iranist literature, there has been a tendency to elaboration and hyperbole. Several scholars have taken a strict and critical view of Kartir from their modern, and so irrelevant, vantage point.\"{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} Zaehner called Kartir a \"religious zealot of quite uncommon ardour\" and to \"the process of intolerance initiated and zestfully developed by Kartir\".{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} Russell called him a \"a ruthless fanatic, Kartir, [who] promoted the xenophobic state cult\", while Folz refers to him as \"fanatical\".{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}} More positive views of Kartir are also found in modern sources, such as Hinz, who called him a \"spiritual man yearning for a religious truth that ought to be revealed to all\", while Neusner described \"the [Sasanian] government\u2019s enthusiasm for Kartir\u2019s program\".{{sfn|Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8|2011|pp=608-628}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kartir's inscription at Naqsh-e Rajab]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Boyce|first=Mary|title=Some reflections on Zurvanism|journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies|publisher=SOAS|location=London|year=1957|volume=19|issue=2|pages=304\u2013316|doi=10.1017/s0041977x00133063 }}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Boyce|first=Mary|title=On the Zoroastrian Temple Cult of Fire|journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society|publisher=AOS/UMich. Press|location=Ann Arbor|volume=95|year=1975|pages=454\u2013465|doi=10.2307/599356|issue=3|jstor=599356}}\n* {{Cite encyclopedia|last=Boyce|first=Mary|year=1975|title=Iconoclasm among Zoroastrians|encyclopedia=Studies for Morton Smith at sixty|location=Leiden|publisher=Neusner|pages=93\u2013111}}.\n* {{cite book |first1=Touraj |last1=Daryaee|first2=Khodadad|last2=Rezakhani|editor1-last=Daryaee |editor1-first=Touraj