{"title_page": "Marcus Liberty", "text_new": "{{Infobox NBA biography\n| name            = Marcus Liberty\n| image           = \n| width           = \n| caption         = \n| number          = 30\n| position        = [[Small forward]]\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 8\n| weight_lb       = 205\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1968|10|27}}\n| birth_place     = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| nationality     = American\n| high_school     = [[King College Prep High School|King College Prep]]<br />(Chicago, Illinois)\n| college         = [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois]] (1988\u20131990)\n| draft_year      = 1990\n| draft_round     = 2\n| draft_pick      = 42\n| draft_team      = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| career_start    = 1990\n| career_end      = 2002\n| years1          = {{nbay|1990|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1993|start}}\n| team1           = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| years2          = {{nbay|1993|full=y}}\n| team2           = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years3          = 1994\u20131995\n| team3           = [[Rapid City Thrillers]]\n| years4          = 1995\u20131996\n| team4           = [[AEK Athens B.C.|AEK Athens]]\n| years5          = 1996\u20131997\n| team5           = [[Ortak\u00f6y Spor Kul\u00fcb\u00fc]]\n| years6          = 1997\n| team6           = [[Fajardo Cariduros|Cariduros de Fajardo]]\n| years7          = 1997\u20131998\n| team7           = [[J\u00e4mtland Basket|J\u00e4mtland Ambassadors \u00d6stersund]]\n| years8          = 1998\n| team8           = [[Polluelos de Aibonito]]\n| years9          = 1998\u20131999\n| team9           = [[Bosch Blue Winds|Zexel Bosch Blue Winds]]\n| years10         = 1999\u20132000\n| team10          = [[Las Vegas Silver Bandits]]\n| years11         = 2000\n| team11          = [[Alaska Aces (PBA)|Alaska Aces]]\n| years12         = 2000\u20132001\n| team12          = [[South Dakota Gold]]\n| years13         = 2001\n| team13          = [[Potros de Villa Francisca]]\n| years14         = 2001\u20132002\n| team14          = Espa\u00f1ol de Talca\n| highlights      = \n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1986, 1987)\n* [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]] (1987)\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label      = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value      = 1,942 (7.3 ppg)\n| stat2label      = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value      = 925 (3.5 rpg)\n| bbr             = liberma01\n}}\n'''Marcus Liberty''' (born October 27, 1968) is an American former professional [[basketball]] player. He played four seasons in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). Liberty played college basketball for the [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|University of Illinois]].\n\n==High school==\nAfter leading Chicago's Crane High School Cougars to a sophomore city title as a freshman, Liberty transferred to Chicago's [[King College Prep High School]] for his sophomore through senior seasons from 1984 to 1987.  During his time at King, Liberty led his basketball teams to an [[Illinois high school boys basketball championship#1982-1991|IHSA State Championship]] in 1986 and a second-place finish in 1987.  During the 1987 tournament run, Liberty scored 41, 23, 38 and 41 points consecutively.  His 143-point effort during that tournament stands as a ''class AA'' record in the state of Illinois. He was named a McDonald's All-American in 1987,<ref>[http://blogs.suntimes.com/hoopsreport/2012/02/states_mcds_all-americans_brea.html Illinois McD's All-Americans breakdown] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523094555/http://blogs.suntimes.com/hoopsreport/2012/02/states_mcds_all-americans_brea.html |date=2013-05-23 }}</ref> as well as the ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' Player of the Year.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1987-03-22/sports/8701220420_1_tourney-record-lincoln-class-aa-title Lincoln Rocks King For Class Aa Title]</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Liberty was voted one of the \"[[100 Legends of the IHSA Boys Basketball Tournament]],\" recognizing his superior performance in his appearances in the tournament.<ref>[http://www.ihsa.org/initiatives/legends/index.htm IHSA - Legends of Boys Basketball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was considered the top senior prep player in the nation by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.\n\n==College and NBA==\nLiberty played [[college basketball|collegiately]] at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]], and was a member of the team that advanced to the 1989 [[1989 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Final Four]]. That [[Fighting Illini]] team gained the moniker \"''[[1988\u201389 Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball team|Flyin' Illini]]''\" by [[Dick Vitale]] while broadcasting a game during the 1988-89 season.  Along with Liberty, the other members of that team included [[Nick Anderson]], [[Kendall Gill]], [[Stephen Bardo]], [[Kenny Battle]], and [[Lowell Hamilton]]. He was then selected by the [[Denver Nuggets]] in the 2nd round (42nd overall) of the [[1990 NBA Draft]]. A 6'8\" (2.03 m) and 205&nbsp;lb (93&nbsp;kg) [[small forward]], Liberty played for the Nuggets and [[Detroit Pistons]] in 4 NBA seasons. His best year as a pro was during the [[1991-92 NBA season]] when he appeared in 75 games for the Nuggets, averaging 9.3 ppg.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.basketpedya.com/Acc002InfJug.php?idjug=2017 basketpedya.com]\n*[http://www.basketballreference.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=LIBERMA01 Marcus Liberty NBA statistics], ''basketballreference.com''\n*[http://www.ihsa.org/activity/bkb/records/allstate.htm''IHSA All-State List'']\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Illinois Mr. Basketball]] Award Winner | before=[[Nick Anderson]] | years=1987| after=[[Eric Anderson (basketball, born 1970)|Eric Anderson]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{USA Today National Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{1990 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liberty, Marcus}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:AEK B.C. players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Chile]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Greece]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Japan]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Sweden]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Turkey]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1989 NCAA Men's Division I Final Four]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Denver Nuggets draft picks]]\n[[Category:Denver Nuggets players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons players]]\n[[Category:Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Silver Bandits players]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (boys' basketball)]]\n[[Category:Rapid City Thrillers players]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NBA biography\n| name            = Marcus Liberty\n| image           = \n| width           = \n| caption         = \n| number          = 30\n| position        = [[Small forward]]\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 8\n| weight_lb       = 205\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1968|10|27}}\n| birth_place     = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| nationality     = American\n| high_school     = [[King College Prep High School|King College Prep]]<br />(Chicago, Illinois)\n| college         = [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois]] (1988\u20131990)\n| draft_year      = 1990\n| draft_round     = 2\n| draft_pick      = 42\n| draft_team      = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| career_start    = 1990\n| career_end      = 2002\n| years1          = {{nbay|1990|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1993|start}}\n| team1           = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| years2          = {{nbay|1993|full=y}}\n| team2           = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years3          = 1994\u20131995\n| team3           = [[Rapid City Thrillers]]\n| years4          = 1995\u20131996\n| team4           = [[AEK Athens B.C.|AEK Athens]]\n| years5          = 1996\u20131997\n| team5           = [[Ortak\u00f6y Spor Kul\u00fcb\u00fc]]\n| years6          = 1997\n| team6           = [[Fajardo Cariduros|Cariduros de Fajardo]]\n| years7          = 1997\u20131998\n| team7           = [[J\u00e4mtland Basket|J\u00e4mtland Ambassadors \u00d6stersund]]\n| years8          = 1998\n| team8           = [[Polluelos de Aibonito]]\n| years9          = 1998\u20131999\n| team9           = [[Bosch Blue Winds|Zexel Bosch Blue Winds]]\n| years10         = 1999\u20132000\n| team10          = [[Las Vegas Silver Bandits]]\n| years11         = 2000\n| team11          = [[Alaska Aces (PBA)|Alaska Aces]]\n| years12         = 2000\u20132001\n| team12          = [[South Dakota Gold]]\n| years13         = 2001\n| team13          = [[Potros de Villa Francisca]]\n| years14         = 2001\u20132002\n| team14          = Espa\u00f1ol de Talca\n| highlights      = \n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1986, 1987)\n* [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]] (1987)\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label      = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value      = 1,942 (7.3 ppg)\n| stat2label      = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value      = 925 (3.5 rpg)\n| bbr             = liberma01\n}}\n'''Marcus Liberty''' (born October 27, 1968) is an American former professional [[basketball]] player. He played four seasons in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). Liberty played college basketball for the [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|University of Illinois]].\n\n==High school==\nAfter leading Chicago's Crane High School Cougars to a sophomore city title as a freshman, Liberty transferred to Chicago's [[King College Prep High School]] for his sophomore through senior seasons from 1984 to 1987.  During his time at King, Liberty led his basketball teams to an [[Illinois high school boys basketball championship#1982-1991|IHSA State Championship]] in 1986 and a second-place finish in 1987.  During the 1987 tournament run, Liberty scored 41, 23, 38 and 41 points consecutively.  His 143-point effort during that tournament stands as a ''class AA'' record in the state of Illinois. He was named a McDonald's All-American in 1987,<ref>[http://blogs.suntimes.com/hoopsreport/2012/02/states_mcds_all-americans_brea.html Illinois McD's All-Americans breakdown] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523094555/http://blogs.suntimes.com/hoopsreport/2012/02/states_mcds_all-americans_brea.html |date=2013-05-23 }}</ref> as well as the ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' Player of the Year.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1987-03-22/sports/8701220420_1_tourney-record-lincoln-class-aa-title Lincoln Rocks King For Class Aa Title]</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Liberty was voted one of the \"[[100 Legends of the IHSA Boys Basketball Tournament]],\" recognizing his superior performance in his appearances in the tournament.<ref>[http://www.ihsa.org/initiatives/legends/index.htm IHSA - Legends of Boys Basketball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was considered the top senior prep player in the nation by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.\n\n==College and NBA==\nLiberty played [[college basketball|collegiately]] at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]], and was a member of the team that advanced to the 1989 [[1989 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Final Four]]. That [[Fighting Illini]] team gained the moniker \"''[[1988\u201389 Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball team|Flyin' Illini]]''\" by [[Dick Vitale]] while broadcasting a game during the 1988-89 season.  Along with Liberty, the other members of that team included [[Nick Anderson]], [[Kendall Gill]], [[Stephen Bardo]], [[Kenny Battle]], and [[Lowell Hamilton]]. He was then selected by the [[Denver Nuggets]] in the 2nd round (42nd overall) of the [[1990 NBA Draft]]. A 6'8\" (2.03 m) and 205&nbsp;lb (93&nbsp;kg) [[small forward]], Liberty played for the Nuggets and [[Detroit Pistons]] in 4 NBA seasons. His best year as a pro was during the [[1991-92 NBA season]] when he appeared in 75 games for the Nuggets, averaging 9.3 ppg.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.basketpedya.com/Acc002InfJug.php?idjug=2017 basketpedya.com]\n*[http://www.basketballreference.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=LIBERMA01 Marcus Liberty NBA statistics], ''basketballreference.com''\n*[http://www.ihsa.org/activity/bkb/records/allstate.htm''IHSA All-State List'']\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Illinois Mr. Basketball]] Award Winner | before=[[Nick Anderson]] | years=1987| after=[[Eric Anderson (basketball)|Eric Anderson]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{USA Today National Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{1990 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liberty, Marcus}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:AEK B.C. players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Chile]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Greece]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Japan]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Sweden]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Turkey]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1989 NCAA Men's Division I Final Four]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Denver Nuggets draft picks]]\n[[Category:Denver Nuggets players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons players]]\n[[Category:Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Silver Bandits players]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (boys' basketball)]]\n[[Category:Rapid City Thrillers players]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcus_Liberty"}
